## 6. Workflow Automation Engine

### Three-Table Automation Architecture

```
workflows
    │  trigger (json): what starts the workflow (schedule, event, webhook)
    │  steps_count: denormalised count for quick UI display
    │
    ├── workflow_steps
    │       type: generate_content / post_to_social / send_email / wait / condition
    │       config (json): step-specific parameters
    │       position: execution order
    │
    └── workflow_runs
            status: queued / running / completed / failed
            started_at / finished_at: execution timing
            result (json): output or error details
```

### `workflows` Table

```sql
CREATE TABLE `workflows` (
  `user_id`     bigint UNSIGNED,
  `brand_id`    char(36),         -- Optional brand scope
  `name`        varchar(120),
  `status`      varchar(20),      -- active / inactive / draft
  `trigger`     json,             -- Trigger definition (schedule, event type, etc.)
  `steps_count` int UNSIGNED,     -- Denormalised for UI list performance
  `deleted_at`  timestamp         -- Soft delete (added in migration batch 17)
);
UNIQUE KEY `workflows_user_id_name_unique` (user_id, name)
```

### `workflow_steps` Table

```sql
CREATE TABLE `workflow_steps` (
  `workflow_id` char(36),
  `type`        varchar(40),   -- Step type (generate, post, wait, condition, etc.)
  `config`      json,          -- Step-specific configuration
  `position`    int UNSIGNED   -- Execution sequence order
);
KEY `workflow_steps_workflow_id_position_index` (workflow_id, position)
```

The `(workflow_id, position)` composite index ensures steps always load in execution order without an `ORDER BY` sort — critical for workflow execution performance.

### `workflow_runs` Table

```sql
CREATE TABLE `workflow_runs` (
  `workflow_id` char(36),
  `status`      varchar(20),   -- queued / running / completed / failed
  `started_at`  timestamp,
  `finished_at` timestamp,
  `result`      json           -- Output data or error details
);
KEY `workflow_runs_workflow_id_status_index` (workflow_id, status)
```

`finished_at - started_at` enables workflow execution duration analytics — identifying slow or failing automation chains.

